theorem Topology.interior_union_frontier_union_interiorCompl_eq_univ
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X} :
    interior (A : Set X) ∪ frontier A ∪ interior (Aᶜ) =
      (Set.univ : Set X) := by
  classical
  -- Prove the two inclusions separately.
  apply Set.Subset.antisymm
  · -- Everything on the left is certainly in `univ`.
    intro x _; trivial
  · -- Let `x : X` be arbitrary; we show it belongs to the left-hand side.
    intro x _
    -- Use the decomposition `closure A ∪ interior Aᶜ = univ`.
    have h_decomp :
        closure (A : Set X) ∪ interior (Aᶜ) = (Set.univ : Set X) :=
      Topology.closure_union_interiorCompl (A := A)
    have hx_union : x ∈ closure (A : Set X) ∪ interior (Aᶜ) := by
      -- Rewrite `x ∈ univ` using `h_decomp`.
      have : x ∈ (Set.univ : Set X) := by trivial
      simpa [h_decomp] using this
    -- Distinguish the two cases provided by the union.
    cases hx_union with
    | inr hx_intCompl =>
        -- Case `x ∈ interior Aᶜ`.
        have : x ∈
            interior (A : Set X) ∪ frontier A ∪ interior (Aᶜ) :=
          Or.inr (Set.mem_union.2 <| Or.inr hx_intCompl)
        simpa using this
    | inl hx_clA =>
        -- Case `x ∈ closure A`; decide whether `x ∈ interior A`.
        by_cases hx_intA : x ∈ interior (A : Set X)
        · -- Subcase `x ∈ interior A`.
          have : x ∈
              interior (A : Set X) ∪ frontier A ∪ interior (Aᶜ) :=
            Or.inl hx_intA
          simpa using this
        · -- Subcase `x ∉ interior A`; then `x` is in the frontier of `A`.
          have hx_frontier : x ∈ frontier (A : Set X) :=
            ⟨hx_clA, hx_intA⟩
          have : x ∈
              interior (A : Set X) ∪ frontier A ∪ interior (Aᶜ) :=
            Or.inr (Set.mem_union.2 <| Or.inl hx_frontier)
          simpa using this
